"Given these results, it is natural to ask: does anything break
down when larger maximum masses are considered? The
positive answer to this question is contained in Fig. 3, whose
panels are similar to those in Fig. 2, when however the genetic
algorithm is forced to consider two specific values of the
maximum mass, namely, 𝑀TOV = 2.4 𝑀� and 𝑀TOV = 2.5 𝑀�.
Concentrating first on the left panel of Fig. 3, it is clear
that when allowing for large maximum masses, the mass
radiated in GWs after the merger, 𝑀postGW (red dashed line), is
significantly larger than what NR simulations predict; this is
true both for 𝑀TOV = 2.4 𝑀� and for 𝑀TOV = 2.5 𝑀�. This
behaviour is due to the fact that remnants with a given 𝜒 will
radiate more GWs if they are more massive [cf., Eq. (9)].
Next, when considering the right panel of Fig. 3 it is also
easy to realize that large maximum masses lead to a deficit
in the ejected matter. This is simply due to the fact that
considering large-mass stars inevitably reduces the portion of
the budget available for the ejecta. We have confirmed that,
even if (unrealistically) large additional angular momentum
transport was assumed, these results remain unchanged for
𝑀TOV & 2.5 𝑀�, (see Supplemental Material)."
"In summary, while a value 𝑀TOV . 2.3 𝑀� is fully con-
sistent with the GW emission from NR simulations and the
observed ejected mass, a value 𝑀TOV & 2.5 𝑀� requires effi-
ciencies in the GW emission that are well above the estimates
from a large number of accurate NR simulations and, overall,
leads to an under-production of ejected mass."
